WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:02.379 --> 00:00:07.059
Keli Carender: Just seems like something The
Onion came up with. Just putting the word

00:00:07.059 --> 00:00:11.140
micro in front of aggression because it's
not a big aggression, it's just a micro one.

00:00:11.140 --> 00:00:20.570
Louis Chude-Sokei: Microaggression is supposed
to be small, seemingly innocent, sometimes

00:00:20.570 --> 00:00:25.169
unintentional, naive or ignorant interactions.

00:00:25.169 --> 00:00:36.130
Mark Olsen: The things that are done unintentionally
that are,

00:00:36.130 --> 00:00:36.810
that can be viewed as derogatory, pejorative.

00:00:36.810 --> 00:00:42.220
Tariqa Waters: I think microaggressions are
bullsh- I'm sorry, I'm trying not to curse,

00:00:42.220 --> 00:00:49.980
but that is just, it's just too much of, you
know, just over explaining your ignorance.

00:00:49.980 --> 00:00:53.850
Microaggressions, I don't think that, when
you're receiving it, they're,

00:00:53.850 --> 00:00:59.050
they're not micro. I think it's easier for the person
who is doing it to use that term.

00:00:59.050 --> 00:01:02.760
Rachael DeCruz: Microaggressions to me are
sort of like those small little actions or

00:01:02.760 --> 00:01:06.719
comments that communicate to people that they're
less than or aren't worthy.

00:01:06.719 --> 00:01:11.409
Cynthia Tee: One of my black students, she
often gets approached and told that she's

00:01:11.409 --> 00:01:20.770
very articulate. And so there's a microaggression
there, because it comes from people who just

00:01:20.770 --> 00:01:24.310
unknown to them automatically assume that
a lot of black people are not very articulate.

00:01:24.310 --> 00:01:27.939
Rachael DeCruz: “You're so smart, you're
so eloquent” and I feel like the piece that

00:01:27.939 --> 00:01:31.929
they're leaving off is like, “despite that
you're a woman of color.” “Oh, you're

00:01:31.929 --> 00:01:35.899
standing out from this group of people that
I had previously thought something else of.”

00:01:35.899 --> 00:01:40.380
Marcelas Owens: It’s like when people tell
me that I don't act like a regular black person.

00:01:40.380 --> 00:01:45.159
Tariqa: “Oh, you look like you came out
of the African gallery.” As beautiful as

00:01:45.159 --> 00:01:51.920
you know my ancestry and my culture is, and
“Good for you working here. Good for you.”

00:01:51.920 --> 00:01:52.899
A lot of that.

00:01:52.899 --> 00:01:57.979
Sean Riley: They may not feel like much individually
but they, they add up. And to me they are

00:01:57.979 --> 00:02:05.740
little fractures that, that spotlight racism.
We see that you do think another is inferior

00:02:05.740 --> 00:02:07.829
or that you are superior.

00:02:07.829 --> 00:02:12.070
Rachael: It’s traumatizing. And it's also
just kind of a constant reminder that the

00:02:12.070 --> 00:02:17.200
world you walk in and you live in wasn't made
for you, and isn't always safe for you.

00:02:17.200 --> 00:02:21.590
Varisha Khan: It makes me feel like I don't
belong in the country that I was born in.

00:02:21.590 --> 00:02:27.340
Microaggressions to me are asking wouldn't
I like to let my hair down just once, or wouldn’t

00:02:27.340 --> 00:02:33.060
I like to wear a swimsuit on a beach just
once. I'm suddenly reminded that I'm not seen

00:02:33.060 --> 00:02:38.180
for my character, or for my actions, or for
how good I am as a person. Rather, I'm just

00:02:38.180 --> 00:02:39.500
seen for the headscarf that's on my head.

00:02:39.500 --> 00:02:42.300
Autumn Bennett: If I say “Oh, like I can
definitely see that you may be Asian, because

00:02:42.300 --> 00:02:46.150
I can tell like, by your eyes.” Is that
a microaggression?

00:02:46.150 --> 00:02:49.770
M. Lorena González: You think you're giving
a compliment but you're really not.

00:02:49.770 --> 00:02:52.270
Rachael: It's like, “Oh, you're so exotic
looking.”

00:02:52.270 --> 00:02:56.650
Leija Farr: Like, when a guy will tell me
that I'm pretty. And then he'll say like,

00:02:56.650 --> 00:03:02.520
um, "Oh, so what are you mixed with?" And
I'm like, "Um, I'm black." That's a microaggression.

00:03:02.520 --> 00:03:06.540
Like they're basically trying to tell you
that just being pure black, you can't be beautiful,

00:03:06.540 --> 00:03:07.980
you have to be mixed with something.

00:03:07.980 --> 00:03:11.680
Autumn: People ask me all the time like, “What
nationality are you?” And I'm like, “Well,

00:03:11.680 --> 00:03:15.150
you know my mom is Syrian and Czechoslovakian
and my dad was Haitian, and I think that's

00:03:15.150 --> 00:03:18.670
frigging cool.” What if people are just
like, being curious?

00:03:18.670 --> 00:03:22.630
Varisha: People ask us if, you know, we do
speak English. They'll kind of talk slowly

00:03:22.630 --> 00:03:26.540
and try to make sense of the words we're saying,
or it's as if they're trying to process the

00:03:26.540 --> 00:03:30.040
fact that we actually are speaking fluent
English. This is my first language.

00:03:30.040 --> 00:03:34.540
Keli: When we think of the word "aggressive"
I think that that is, you know, deliberate

00:03:34.540 --> 00:03:39.150
to make it seem like it's a little bit more
than offensive, like it's almost a physical

00:03:39.150 --> 00:03:41.600
attack, you know, almost like they're touching
you.

