Jerrell Davis: When I was at SPU, I used to
have a Afro. Kids would come up behind me

00:03:48.100 --> 00:03:53.750
and touch my hair. Like no permission, I don't
know them, come up behind me, and touch my

00:03:53.750 --> 00:03:58.780
hair. And I turn around and slap their hand
away, I’m like “What are you doing?”

00:03:58.780 --> 00:04:04.210
They're like, "it's just so soft. It just
looks so soft, I just wanted to touch it."

00:04:04.210 --> 00:04:09.750
Look, let me come up behind a white girl and
start touching her hair.

00:04:09.750 --> 00:04:10.370
I'm locked up with the quickness.

00:04:10.370 --> 00:04:14.770
Leija: Some people might see that as, like,
nice, but I really don't. I feel like that

00:04:14.770 --> 00:04:19.090
is kind of offensive to, like, ask somebody,
can you touch their hair. Like if their hair

00:04:19.090 --> 00:04:21.329
is in a style that you're not used to.

00:04:21.329 --> 00:04:28.370
Tariqa: It's this weird, you know like, fetish,
weird thing that white people have with our

00:04:28.370 --> 00:04:32.920
hair that's absolutely, I don't know what
it is.

00:04:32.920 --> 00:04:40.790
Lorena: A couple years ago during Halloween
was parking my car in a garage in downtown,

00:04:40.790 --> 00:04:48.120
and this older white gentleman saw me get
out of my car, and he's very, very social.

00:04:48.120 --> 00:04:57.650
And he asked me what they call Halloween in
my country. And I told him, “Well, they

00:04:57.650 --> 00:05:08.530
call it Halloween, because this is my country.”
To be honest I cared less about how he felt

00:05:08.530 --> 00:05:15.250
about being the microaggressor and more about
how it made me feel.

00:05:15.250 --> 00:05:21.310
It's about the impact, and not about the intent of the person who, who engaged in that behavior.

00:05:21.310 --> 00:05:30.370
Keli: We've gone really far in saying it's
all about what the person receiving it thinks

00:05:30.370 --> 00:05:31.760
that it means.

00:05:31.760 --> 00:05:35.770
Autumn: I also think it has to do with like,
people just not really having like a backbone.

00:05:35.770 --> 00:05:41.530
And I think we've become this society where
these like, kids are these like, delicate

00:05:41.530 --> 00:05:44.570
orchids that just wilt once they leave the
greenhouse, they just die.

00:05:44.570 --> 00:05:48.810
Tariqa: I'd rather for them to just call me
a nigger, because it would have been easier

00:05:48.810 --> 00:05:54.200
to take. It's easier to take just you know,
just overt, you know, just racial slurs than

00:05:54.200 --> 00:06:01.410
the way people try to dress it up as not being
a racial exchange at all.

00:06:01.410 --> 00:06:04.889
Keli: I don't know, it just seems, it just
seems ridiculous, and there's just like so

00:06:04.889 --> 00:06:08.490
many things to remember now that you're not supposed to say, you can't do, you can't think it.

00:06:08.490 --> 00:06:08.740
it.

00:06:08.740 --> 00:06:14.270
every little thing I say and do? It feels
very painful, it feels very tedious to do that.”

00:06:14.270 --> 00:06:21.230
And my response to that is “Yes.
For you now finally in your adult life to

00:06:21.230 --> 00:06:26.560
that.” And my response to that is “Yes.
For you now finally in your adult life to

00:06:26.560 --> 00:06:36.060
experience this effort, it's about time, because
the people that you have done this microaggression

00:06:36.060 --> 00:06:38.300
to have experienced it all their lives.”

00:06:38.310 --> 00:06:43.440
Louis: People who are hostile to the notion
of microaggressions assume that games are

00:06:43.440 --> 00:06:48.460
being played. Assume that this is actually
driven by specific political agendas. It's

00:06:48.460 --> 00:06:56.419
the victim card. I think people don't understand that
there's actually pain there. I'm really split on

00:06:56.419 --> 00:07:01.639
the issue of microaggressions. You know, because
I don't want to deny anyone's pain, but I

00:07:01.639 --> 00:07:10.699
also don't, can't imagine a world where interacting
with difference is done without pain.

